7 SECTION 5. G.S. 14-33(c)(4) reads as rewritten:
8 "(4) Assaults an officer or employee of the State or any political subdivision of the
9 State, State (i) when the officer or employee is discharging or attempting to
10 discharge his or her official duties;duties or (ii) because of the victim's status
11 as an officer or employee of the State or any political subdivision of the State."
12 SECTION 6. G.S. 14-34.2 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 14-34.2. Assault with a firearm or other deadly weapon upon governmental officers or
14 employees, company police officers, or campus police officers.
15 Unless a person's conduct is covered under some other provision of law providing greater
16 punishment, any person who commits an assault with a deadly weapon upon an officer or
17 employee of the State or of any political subdivision of the State, a company police officer
18 certified pursuant to the provisions of Chapter 74E of the General Statutes, or a campus police
19 officer certified pursuant to the provisions of Chapter 74G, Article 1 of Chapter 17C or Chapter
20 116 of the General Statutes, (i) in the performance of an official duty or (ii) because of the victim's
21 status as an officer or employee of the State or of any political subdivision of the State, a company
22 police officer, or a campus police officer, is guilty of a Class E felony."
23 SECTION 7. G.S. 14-34.5 reads as rewritten:
24 "§ 14-34.5. Assault with a firearm on a law enforcement, probation, or parole officer, or
25 on a member of the North Carolina National Guard, or on a person employed at
26 a State or local detention facility.public safety officer.
27 (a) Any person who commits an assault with a firearm upon a law enforcement officer,
28 probation officer, or parole public safety officer (i) while the officer is in the performance of his
29 or her duties or (ii) because of the victim's status as a public safety officer is guilty of a Class D
30 felony.
31 (a1) Any person who commits an assault with a firearm upon a member of the North
32 Carolina National Guard while the member is in the performance of his or her duties is guilty of
33 a Class D felony.
34 (b) Anyone who commits an assault with a firearm upon a person who is employed at a
35 detention facility operated under the jurisdiction of the State or a local government while the
36 employee is in the performance of the employee's duties is guilty of a Class D felony.
37 (c) For purposes of this section, the term "public safety officer" is as defined in
38 G.S. 14-34.7A."
39 SECTION 8. G.S. 14-34.6 is repealed.
40 SECTION 9. G.S. 14-34.7 reads as rewritten:
41 "§ 14-34.7. Certain assaults Assault or affray on a law enforcement, probation, or parole
42 officer, or on a member of the North Carolina National Guard, or on a person
43 employed at a State or local detention facility; public safety officer; penalty.
44 (a) Unless covered under some other provision of law providing greater punishment, a
45 person is guilty of a Class E felony if the person assaults commits an assault or affray on a law
46 enforcement officer, probation officer, or parole public safety officer (i) while the officer is
47 discharging or attempting to discharge his or her official duties or (ii) because of the victim's
48 status as a public safety officer, and inflicts serious bodily injury on the officer.
49 (a1) Unless covered under some other provision of law providing greater punishment, a
50 person is guilty of a Class E felony if the person assaults a member of the North Carolina National
