21 defined in G.S. 14-34.7A and the term "physical injury" includes cuts, scrapes, bruises, or other
22 physical injury which does not constitute serious injury."
23 SECTION 10. G.S. 14-69.3 reads as rewritten:
24 "§ 14-69.3. Arson or other unlawful burning that results in serious bodily injury or serious
25 injury to a firefighter, law enforcement officer, public safety officer or fire
26 investigator, or emergency medical technician.investigator.
27 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
28 (1) Emergency medical technician. – The term includes an emergency medical
29 technician, an advanced emergency medical technician, and an emergency
30 medical technician-paramedic, as those terms are defined in G.S. 131E-155.
31 (2) Fire investigator. – The term includes any person who, individually or as part
32 of an investigative team, has the responsibility and authority to determine the
33 origin, cause, or development of a fire or explosion.
34 (3) Public safety officer. – As defined in G.S. 14-34.7A.
35 (b) Offense Involving Serious Bodily Injury. – A Unless covered under some other
36 provision of law providing greater punishment, a person is guilty of a Class E felony if (i) the
37 person commits a felony under Article 15 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes and a firefighter,
38 law enforcement officer, public safety officer or fire investigator, or emergency medical
39 technician investigator suffers serious bodily injury while discharging or attempting to discharge
40 official duties on the property, or proximate to the property, that is the subject of the firefighter's,
41 law enforcement officer's, fire investigator's, or emergency medical technician's public safety
42 officer's or fire investigator's discharge or attempt to discharge his or her respective duties.duties
43 or (ii) the person commits a felony under Article 15 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes because
44 of the victim's status as a public safety officer or fire investigator and the public safety officer or
45 fire investigator suffers serious bodily injury.
46 (c) Offense Involving Serious Injury. – A Unless covered under some other provision of
47 law providing greater punishment, a person is guilty of a Class F felony if (i) the person commits
48 a felony under Article 15 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes and a firefighter, law enforcement
49 officer, public safety officer or fire investigator, or emergency medical technician investigator
50 suffers serious injury while discharging or attempting to discharge official duties on the property,
51 or proximate to the property, that is the subject of the firefighter's, law enforcement officer's, fire
